  weaknesses:['Defensive duel win rate: a 62.5% ground duel success rate places him in the 78th percentile for a centre-back. When isolated one-v-one in deeper positions his physical tools do not match his technical ones.','Aerial reliability: Van Hecke is not a dominant aerial defender. His height is adequate but his heading is not a weapon. Set-piece vulnerability is a known risk in De Zerbi systems already.','Contract leverage: Brighton lost him for 52 million pounds despite Chelsea and Liverpool interest. He is a one-club man in terms of destination, which signals potential limitations in ambition or negotiating leverage at the next level.'],
  callout:{title:'Is 52 million pounds too much for a defender with one year left on his contract?',body:"On the surface, paying 52 million pounds for a player who could have been signed for free in twelve months is hard to justify, and it is exactly the kind of deal that gets Premier League directors sacked. But the context matters. Van Hecke was the single most progressive ball-carrying centre-back in the league last season, and the two clubs offering alternatives in Chelsea and Liverpool were also willing to pay that price. Brighton drove the fee by leaking interest, imposing a tight deadline, and exploiting Tottenham's desperation for De Zerbi's preferred system. The Seagulls extracted a premium for a player in the final year of his deal, a masterclass in leverage rather than a fair reflection of footballing value. For Tottenham, the decision is really about whether the system requires him specifically, and De Zerbi's track record of building teams around exactly this profile suggests it probably does."},
  projection:{title:'Projection and risk',body:"Van Hecke is 26 heading into the peak years of a centre-back's career, and the step up to a Champions League-chasing club under the manager who built him is a reasonable bet on continued growth. The risk is tactical dependency. His numbers are partly a product of Brighton's philosophy, and if Tottenham's system is less possession-dominated, the progression metrics could soften. Durability has been excellent, but a significant injury could expose the fact that he is more of a system player than an elite individual stopper. The ceiling is a consistent top-ten European centre-back. The floor is a 52-million-pound squad player who works best in one specific system."},
  sources:['FBref / Opta','Transfermarkt','DataMB via X @DataMB_','Total Football Analysis','One-vs-One.com','FotMob','Sky Sports and The Athletic'],
